00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:26.430
PROFESSOR: So the
subject here is about

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:30.830
if you want to
understand interactions

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:31.990
between neutral objects.

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:50.870
So let's start in
a very basic way

00:00:50.870 --> 00:00:57.380
by saying we have an atome
A, we have an atom B,

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:02.680
they are separated
by a distance R,

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:09.130
and we want to know what
is the force between them.

00:01:09.130 --> 00:01:11.500
In a semiclassical
picture, we would

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:18.530
say that everything
is-- the force which

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:22.670
is responsible for that
must be the Coulomb force.

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:28.670
So the atom A and B
consists of charges,

00:01:28.670 --> 00:01:31.160
so we should find
the charge density

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:35.262
in our system A, the
charge density of B,

00:01:35.262 --> 00:01:44.880
we take the coulomb energy and
we integrate over the volume.

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:49.930
And this is how in e and
m, in the most general way,

00:01:49.930 --> 00:01:55.760
you would to write down
the electrostatic energy

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:56.720
of a system.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:59.720
You take all
charges, each charge

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:02.270
has a coulomb potential with
the other charge [INAUDIBLE]

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:04.540
indicate over everything.

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:10.080
But for objects
which are localized

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:15.810
and we can do
multiple expansion,

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:18.410
our objects are
neutral, neutral atom.

00:02:18.410 --> 00:02:20.740
So therefore there
is no coulomb term,

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:25.090
and the next term is the dipole.

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:31.900
So therefore, starting
with classical physics,

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:41.130
we would find that the
interaction of those charge

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:47.770
density distributions one
for atom A, one for atom B,

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:51.990
should actually interact with
this Hamiltonian h prime.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:13.200
OK, but now, if you
look at it classically,

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:18.100
we find that classically,
the expectation

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:21.220
value for the dipole operator
of each atom is zero.

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:26.870
But you will also
find-- if you said,

00:03:26.870 --> 00:03:29.650
well, OK, that's what I
expect, because an atom

00:03:29.650 --> 00:03:31.280
is in isotopic space.

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.000
How can it have a dipole moment?

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.170
But maybe, what could
happen is, if there

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.810
is a fluctuation of
a dipole moment here

00:03:38.810 --> 00:03:42.560
and a fluctuation there and the
fluctuations are correlated,

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:45.450
then the two systems may
repel or attract each other.

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:49.360
So therefore, when we are
talking about fluctuations,

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.990
we are talking about expectation
values for d squared.

00:03:53.990 --> 00:03:59.090
But also in classical
physics, this is exactly zero.

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:02.210
So what classical
physics tells us,

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:04.990
it says, in
classical physics, it

00:04:04.990 --> 00:04:10.450
costs more energy to create
a dipole moment, or even

00:04:10.450 --> 00:04:13.554
a fluctuating dipole
moment, than one gets back

00:04:13.554 --> 00:04:14.720
from the dipole interaction.

00:04:17.630 --> 00:04:20.240
So the system will
never spontaneously form

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:21.899
some form of dipole moment.

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:24.600
And in classical physics,
two neutral atoms

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.598
will have no attraction at all.

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:34.225
So it costs more energy.

00:05:03.110 --> 00:05:06.610
So now, we have to
do quantum mechanics.

00:05:06.610 --> 00:05:11.120
And every so often, I have to
go through a classical argument

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:14.310
to make you wonder about the
quantum mechanical result.

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:16.840
Because the quantum mechanical
result, you're used to it.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:19.230
You've heard about the
van der Waals interaction.

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:22.010
But now you know
that there is really

00:05:22.010 --> 00:05:24.110
something quantum at work.

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:32.350
In quantum mechanics,
the expectation value

00:05:32.350 --> 00:05:37.080
of the square of the dipole
operator is not zero.

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:41.990
I mean, you can see that if
you have an electron, which

00:05:41.990 --> 00:05:44.910
is in an harmonic
oscillator, and if it

00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:53.760
is at the bottom of
the oscillator-- well,

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:57.150
the dipole moment--
what I want you to say

00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:00.300
is the dipole moment
for a charged system

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:04.210
is related to-- between
electron and proton--

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:07.980
to the displacement operator, R.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.380
And even if you have an
equilibrium position--

00:06:10.380 --> 00:06:13.360
like in an harmonic oscillator,
where R is equal to zero,

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:16.480
R squared-- the expectation
value-- is not zero,

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:18.940
because whatever your
stable equilibrium is,

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:21.490
you will have zero point
fluctuations around it.

00:06:21.490 --> 00:06:24.300
And so therefore, now
in quantum physics,

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:29.980
it's not that we have to provide
energy to create a d squared.

00:06:29.980 --> 00:06:30.850
We have it.

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:34.640
We have it by necessity, because
of non-commuting operators,

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:37.680
because of the nature
of the quantum physics.

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:40.920
So now, the fact that we have
fluctuating dipole moments

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.750
already, that means if now
with the fluctuating dipole

00:06:44.750 --> 00:06:48.510
moments between the two
atoms are synchronized,

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:51.750
this will then lead to a
non-vanishing average force

00:06:51.750 --> 00:06:53.230
between the atoms.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:55.100
So that's the idea.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:57.690
But the good thing
is, you don't even

00:06:57.690 --> 00:07:00.780
have to know about it-- about
fluctuations and all that.

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:03.550
You just take-- and
this is your homework--

00:07:03.550 --> 00:07:09.060
you just take the
operator H prime.

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:12.160
And look what happens when
you have an atom in the ground

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:15.800
and excited state
and what happens

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:18.550
when you have both atoms
in the ground state.

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:22.450
In the first case, you
get the leading result

00:07:22.450 --> 00:07:25.600
in first order
perturbation theory.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:30.190
For two ground state atoms,
you have to go to second order.

00:07:30.190 --> 00:07:38.880
In first order, the
potential is 1 over R cubed.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:42.420
And you will calculate
the C3 coefficient.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:45.480
In second order, you get
a van der Waals potential,

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:48.180
which is 1 over R to the sixth.

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:51.380
And it's fairly
straightforward to calculate

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:52.570
the C6 coefficient.

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:01.110
Any questions?

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:14.000
So let me reemphasize, the
beauty of this perturbation

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:15.950
result that it's so simple.

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:17.640
But the downside
is, you don't really

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:18.850
understand what you're doing.

00:08:18.850 --> 00:08:20.891
I mean, you are solving
the Schrodinger equation.

00:08:20.891 --> 00:08:22.710
You are finding an
expectation value.

00:08:22.710 --> 00:08:25.490
But the nature of
the effect-- how

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:28.420
it is related to fluctuation,
what is really behind it--

00:08:28.420 --> 00:08:31.640
is sometimes obscured.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:34.031
So let me give you one
interpretation, which I really

00:08:34.031 --> 00:08:34.530
like.

00:08:40.610 --> 00:08:43.379
And I learned that
actually from Dan Kleppner.

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:51.120
When he taught the atomic
physics course at MIT

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:55.620
20 years ago, that
was one element of it.

00:08:55.620 --> 00:08:57.830
And I told you at the
beginning that I'm actually

00:08:57.830 --> 00:09:01.310
proud that our atomic
physics course is really

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:04.200
kind of-- has hopefully
kept-- the best of the decade

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:07.550
long tradition of teachers
like Norman Ramsey, Dan

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:09.190
Kleppner, and Dave Pritchard.

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:11.860
So this is now really
due to Dan Kleppner.

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:14.570
And I will later
today actually post

00:09:14.570 --> 00:09:18.480
Dan Kleppner's original lecture
notes about this effect.

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:22.190
So we want to understand
the van der Waals

00:09:22.190 --> 00:09:24.640
force in a completely
different system.

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:26.410
And I think that helps.

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:31.025
We have two LC circuits.

00:09:34.634 --> 00:09:44.510
There's L, C, C, L.

00:09:44.510 --> 00:09:52.310
And what happens is, the
two capacitors are closed.

00:09:52.310 --> 00:09:54.937
So there is this stray field
of one capacitor reaching

00:09:54.937 --> 00:09:55.770
the other capacitor.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:03.590
So I won't go through
the detailed math here,

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:05.630
because it's not necessary.

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:08.420
But what we have
here is, we have

00:10:08.420 --> 00:10:12.440
two coupled systems--
two coupled capacitors.

00:10:15.450 --> 00:10:18.790
And the only thing
I want to use is

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:21.260
that the stray
field of a capacitor

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.360
has a diopolic characteristic.

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:27.310
And it decays with
1 over R cubed.

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:36.150
So what we have right
now is, each LC circuit,

00:10:36.150 --> 00:10:38.870
when it's isolated, has
a resonant frequency

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:41.810
of omega naught.

00:10:41.810 --> 00:10:45.010
But now, when we have two
pendulums-- two oscillators--

00:10:45.010 --> 00:10:47.970
which are coupled,
we get two modes,

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:51.950
which are omega plus and minus.

00:10:51.950 --> 00:10:54.790
And if we simply
solve for two modes,

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:57.030
and they have some
coupling, well, we

00:10:57.030 --> 00:11:00.690
get an upshift and
downshift by the coupling.

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:04.090
But if you look more carefully
at the solution for two

00:11:04.090 --> 00:11:07.670
coupled modes, it has
also a quadratic effect,

00:11:07.670 --> 00:11:11.830
which is sometimes
neglected, but it's there.

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:13.400
So this is, in
general, what you will

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:16.970
find, if you couple two modes.

00:11:16.970 --> 00:11:22.400
Now in quantum
mechanics, when we

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:29.830
ask for the oscillator
in the ground state,

00:11:29.830 --> 00:11:32.295
we can find the
zero point energy.

00:11:36.970 --> 00:11:39.650
And so the energy
in the ground state

00:11:39.650 --> 00:11:45.325
is 1/2 the zero point
energy in the mode plus,

00:11:45.325 --> 00:11:47.890
in the mode minus.

00:11:47.890 --> 00:11:53.730
The first order coupling term,
the 1 over R cubed cancels out.

00:11:53.730 --> 00:11:57.670
But what remains
is a contribution,

00:11:57.670 --> 00:11:59.150
which is 1 over R to the sixth.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:07.160
So we need quantum physics.

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:16.050
Because in classical
physics, the ground state

00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:19.910
of the LC circuit
is nothing happens.

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:22.022
No charge, no
current, no nothing.

00:12:22.022 --> 00:12:23.730
I mean, this is a
classical ground state,

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:25.890
and you would not
get any effect.

00:12:25.890 --> 00:12:31.480
So realize that this van
der Waals potential requires

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:42.980
quantum mechanics, and it
is due to the zero point

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:51.435
energy of the
atomic oscillators.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.400
Just hold the
thought, when we talk

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:09.210
about atoms in the
electromagnetic field,

00:13:09.210 --> 00:13:10.880
we have two oscillators.

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:12.590
We have an harmonic
oscillator, which

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:16.000
is a fluctuating dipole moment
on each side of the atom.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.190
But we have many, many harmonic
oscillators in between,

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:21.750
which is the
electromagnetic field.

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:26.870
And during the course
of this lecture,

00:13:26.870 --> 00:13:30.520
I will refer to
both the zero point

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:34.340
energy of the atomic
oscillator and the zero point

00:13:34.340 --> 00:13:38.110
energy of the oscillator, which
is the electromagnetic field.

00:13:38.110 --> 00:13:42.840
And to give you the
result at the end,

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:46.110
I will sort of explain
different effects

00:13:46.110 --> 00:13:49.380
by the zero point oscillation
of the atoms, other effects

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:53.060
by the zero point oscillation
of the electromagnetic field.

00:13:53.060 --> 00:13:55.990
But at the end of this
section, which is probably

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.350
after spring break on
Monday, I will actually

00:13:58.350 --> 00:14:04.180
tell you that you
have to be careful.

00:14:04.180 --> 00:14:06.630
If you have quantum
physics, you have

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:09.450
to use a consistent description.

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:14.330
And you always need that
both the field and the atoms

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:17.090
are quantized and give
zero point fluctuations.

00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:20.650
And when I'm telling you
now that the van der Waals

00:14:20.650 --> 00:14:22.590
potential is due
only to zero point

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:24.830
fluctuations of the
atomic oscillator,

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:27.880
there may be another way
of getting the same result

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:29.670
by looking at the zero
point fluctuations

00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:32.570
of the electromagnetic field.

00:14:32.570 --> 00:14:36.100
So I just want you
to take what I'm

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:38.480
saying to you-- I'm not
saying to you anything wrong.

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:41.950
But it may not be the
only way of expressing it.

00:14:41.950 --> 00:14:45.480
And I want you just to
pay attention to it.

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:49.880
But certain effects
can be simply described

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:52.390
by just simply looking at
the atomic oscillators.

00:14:52.390 --> 00:14:55.190
Why do we need the quantized
electromagnetic field

00:14:55.190 --> 00:14:57.410
when all we want to do
is have a stray field

00:14:57.410 --> 00:14:58.830
coupling two capacitors.

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:02.315
So we want to always
learn about the simplest

00:15:02.315 --> 00:15:04.190
way to understanding an effect.

00:15:04.190 --> 00:15:08.810
But then in the end, there
are maybe certain subtleties.

00:15:08.810 --> 00:15:09.430
OK.

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:11.150
But let's keep it simple.

00:15:11.150 --> 00:15:15.100
So it's a zero point energy
of the two oscillators.

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:29.100
And maybe let me emphasize
this by translating

00:15:29.100 --> 00:15:34.770
this description-- what we
learned from the capacitors.

00:15:34.770 --> 00:15:38.130
Let me give you the Coulomb
description of the atom.

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:44.140
So an atom really never have in
free space a spontaneous dipole

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:46.500
moment.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:51.940
But because of zero
point oscillation,

00:15:51.940 --> 00:15:55.400
it will have a dipole
moment squared.

00:15:55.400 --> 00:16:01.240
So what happens now is,
let's say at some moment,

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:02.410
we have a fluctuation.

00:16:02.410 --> 00:16:05.090
One atom happens to
have a fluctuation

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:06.730
of the dipole moment.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:20.140
This creates an electric field
at the position of the atom, b.

00:16:20.140 --> 00:16:21.790
So this is a fluctuating field.

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:28.830
The fluctuating
field, because there's

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:39.490
a finite polarizability,
induces now

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:47.460
a dipole moment of the atom, db.

00:16:47.460 --> 00:16:49.610
I will later introduced
polarizabilities.

00:16:49.610 --> 00:16:52.420
But here, it's just
proportional to Eb.

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:57.794
So that's proportional
to da over R cubed.

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:04.619
So now, we have no longer
randomly fluctuating

00:17:04.619 --> 00:17:07.869
dipole moments with da db,
which are out of phase.

00:17:07.869 --> 00:17:10.329
Positive and minus cancels out.

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:13.550
We have a dipole
moment, da, which

00:17:13.550 --> 00:17:18.280
creates-- through
polarizability--

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:21.569
an aligned dipole moment, db.

00:17:21.569 --> 00:17:30.700
And for those, we have now
the dipole-dipole interaction,

00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:36.370
which is db da over R cubed.

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:39.310
And when db changes
sign, da changes signs.

00:17:39.310 --> 00:17:42.300
So the product of them
will always stay the same.

00:17:42.300 --> 00:17:47.110
And now, we find that
we have an interaction.

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:51.360
If you look, db
was 1 over R cubed.

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:54.190
And if you multiply
that with the R

00:17:54.190 --> 00:17:57.500
cubed of the
dipole-dipole interaction,

00:17:57.500 --> 00:18:01.070
we obtain, in a
very different way,

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:06.220
the van der Waals potential,
which is 1 over R to the sixth.

00:18:06.220 --> 00:18:09.810
So therefore, what
we can take away

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:20.830
from that is that the 1 over
R to the sixth potential

00:18:20.830 --> 00:18:34.970
is caused by the zero
point fluctuations

00:18:34.970 --> 00:18:36.510
of the atomic dipole moments.

00:18:49.010 --> 00:18:49.510
OK.

00:18:54.550 --> 00:18:57.900
So now you have already
three different ways

00:18:57.900 --> 00:18:59.840
to look at the van
der Waals potential.

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:01.480
One is just doing
perturbation theory

00:19:01.480 --> 00:19:03.200
and not understanding anything.

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:05.850
The second one is
the ground state

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:09.000
of two coupled oscillators,
a la two capacitors.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:14.310
And finally, the fact that
spontaneous fluctuations create

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:16.730
stimulated fluctuations,
and then there

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:20.590
is a quadratic term,
which doesn't vanish.

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:22.230
OK.

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:30.166
Well, let's now consider that
the electromagnetic field--

00:19:30.166 --> 00:19:31.790
