to an intermediate state.

00:38:15.460 --> 00:38:18.660
And then, you go from the
intermediate state, one,

00:38:18.660 --> 00:38:20.700
to the final state.

00:38:20.700 --> 00:38:22.900
And what you have
to do is, you have

00:38:22.900 --> 00:38:26.745
to divide by the
energy denominator.

00:38:29.410 --> 00:38:34.790
If you do higher and higher
order perturbation theory,

00:38:34.790 --> 00:38:37.010
in our diagrammatic
presentation,

00:38:37.010 --> 00:38:41.760
that means we have propagators
at intermediate energies.

00:38:41.760 --> 00:38:45.020
And I told you that
the time an atom can

00:38:45.020 --> 00:38:49.720
spend in an intermediate state
is 1 over the energy defect.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:58.400
And if you integrate the
E to the i energy defect

00:38:58.400 --> 00:39:00.950
factor over time,
you get something

00:39:00.950 --> 00:39:04.300
which is proportional
to 1 over delta E.

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:08.430
So therefore, if you
perform the time integration

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:12.210
of the perturbation
analysis, you

00:39:12.210 --> 00:39:16.710
find by integrating over the
short time particles spend

00:39:16.710 --> 00:39:18.490
in the intermediate
state, you actually

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:21.030
generate those
energy denominators.

00:39:21.030 --> 00:39:24.860
That's actually the relationship
between the time propagation

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:26.100
I showed you earlier.

00:39:26.100 --> 00:39:28.630
And when you integrate
over the time,

00:39:28.630 --> 00:39:31.410
you get for this intermediate
state, a contribution,

00:39:31.410 --> 00:39:33.780
which is 1 over
the energy defect

00:39:33.780 --> 00:39:36.630
over the intermediate state.

00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:41.650
So therefore, if you go now
to higher order perturbation

00:39:41.650 --> 00:39:51.700
theory, we simply have a
product of matrix elements

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:56.040
in the numerator.

00:39:56.040 --> 00:39:59.735
And in the denominator, we have
a product of energy defects.

00:40:04.640 --> 00:40:08.000
You are using that all the time
for second order perturbation

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.590
theory, but the structure
is that you can just

00:40:11.590 --> 00:40:13.556
sort of daisy chain
the expression.

00:40:13.556 --> 00:40:15.430
And you get higher order
perturbation theory.

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:25.660
So therefore, all we will have
to understand to figure out

00:40:25.660 --> 00:40:28.530
what happens when virtual
photons are exchanged,

00:40:28.530 --> 00:40:31.740
I will just show you
two relevant diagrams.

00:40:31.740 --> 00:40:34.560
And we just look-- we
stare at the diagrams--

00:40:34.560 --> 00:40:37.090
and figure out what
are these denominators?

00:40:37.090 --> 00:40:38.795
What are those energy defects?

00:40:38.795 --> 00:40:40.545
And we will find that
there's a difference

00:40:40.545 --> 00:40:42.190
at long range and short range.

00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:43.140
So that's the agenda.

00:40:46.280 --> 00:40:48.760
So we will need two energies.

00:40:48.760 --> 00:40:51.840
One energy is the energy
of the virtual photon,

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:54.580
which is exchanged.

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:58.080
And the second
energy, or frequency,

00:40:58.080 --> 00:41:05.141
is the resonant
frequency of the atom.

00:41:20.870 --> 00:41:25.820
So let's look at two
relevant diagrams.

00:41:34.540 --> 00:41:38.590
So one is atom,
a; one is atom, b.

00:41:38.590 --> 00:41:41.200
We are interested
in interactions

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:43.740
between atoms in
the ground state.

00:41:43.740 --> 00:41:46.500
And after a
sufficiently long time,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:48.580
both atoms have to be
back in the ground state.

00:41:58.420 --> 00:42:03.550
Let me just get this organized,
one, two, three, four.

00:42:10.530 --> 00:42:14.750
And the result is obtained
in fourth order perturbation

00:42:14.750 --> 00:42:16.590
theory.

00:42:16.590 --> 00:42:18.970
It has to be fourth
order, because we

00:42:18.970 --> 00:42:20.870
need photon exchange.

00:42:20.870 --> 00:42:24.340
To emit a photon here, absorb
it here, is second order.

00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:30.520
But then, one atom is
in the excited state

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:31.630
and this can't be.

00:42:31.630 --> 00:42:34.430
So a second photon is
required to undo the effect.

00:42:34.430 --> 00:42:37.850
So we need exchange
of photon pairs.

00:42:37.850 --> 00:42:40.780
Each exchange means
absorption and emission.

00:42:40.780 --> 00:42:42.200
That means two vertices.

00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:43.980
And photon pairs
means another two.

00:42:43.980 --> 00:42:47.410
So we need fourth order
perturbation theory.

00:42:47.410 --> 00:42:47.910
OK.

00:42:47.910 --> 00:42:52.590
But it's much, much
easier than you think.

00:42:52.590 --> 00:42:54.640
So we have a ground state atom.

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.430
And now the action starts.

00:42:56.430 --> 00:42:57.920
This is the first vertex.

00:42:57.920 --> 00:43:01.240
It emits a photon.

00:43:01.240 --> 00:43:05.380
The photon is absorbed
by the other atom, which

00:43:05.380 --> 00:43:08.990
puts the atom into
the excited state.

00:43:08.990 --> 00:43:11.490
This atom is also in the
excited state, of course.

00:43:24.790 --> 00:43:28.880
And then, we know the atom
cannot stay in the excited

00:43:28.880 --> 00:43:32.210
state for a long time.

00:43:32.210 --> 00:43:37.920
It can now emit a second
photon, which brings it back

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:40.030
to the ground state.

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:45.325
And the second photon
is absorbed by atom, b,

00:43:45.325 --> 00:43:47.200
and puts the atom back
into the ground state.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.520
So this is one relevant diagram.

00:43:53.520 --> 00:44:01.790
And let me analyze it
in the energy defects.

00:44:01.790 --> 00:44:05.320
Here, in the first
intermediate step,

00:44:05.320 --> 00:44:09.670
the energy defect is--
well, we have ground-ground.

00:44:09.670 --> 00:44:12.910
This is sort our reference.

00:44:12.910 --> 00:44:17.070
But now, we have put one
atom into the excited state.

00:44:17.070 --> 00:44:19.630
That causes energy,
omega naught.

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:23.290
And we have created
one photon, omega.

00:44:23.290 --> 00:44:27.100
Here in that time step,
there are no photons,

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:29.740
but there are two excited atoms.

00:44:29.740 --> 00:44:32.700
And in the third time step,
we have still one atom

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:36.280
in the excited state
and one photon.

00:44:39.810 --> 00:44:43.250
Now, this is one relevant class.

00:44:43.250 --> 00:44:46.200
I mean, you can now use
permutations at atom, b,

00:44:46.200 --> 00:44:47.930
excites photons first and such.

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:50.570
But the structure of
many of these diagrams

00:44:50.570 --> 00:44:55.360
will be the same that we have
those three energy defects.

00:44:55.360 --> 00:44:57.540
But now, we have
another possibility.

00:44:57.540 --> 00:45:01.420
And this is, one
atom emits a photon,

00:45:01.420 --> 00:45:06.570
but it feels it doesn't
want to be excited,

00:45:06.570 --> 00:45:09.930
because the excitation
energy is so precious.

00:45:09.930 --> 00:45:12.760
It wants to immediately
return to the ground state.

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:16.170
So we could have a situation
that the atom fires

00:45:16.170 --> 00:45:21.140
a second photon before the
first photon is absorbed.

00:45:23.860 --> 00:45:29.370
So the diagram-- the relevant
diagram-- is now this.

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:36.220
So the atom started
in the ground state,

00:45:36.220 --> 00:45:39.460
is in the excited state,
but as soon as possible,

00:45:39.460 --> 00:45:42.550
goes back to the ground state.

00:45:42.550 --> 00:45:46.080
And the other atom starts
out in ground state,

00:45:46.080 --> 00:45:49.470
is in the excited state, and
is back in the ground state.

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:55.360
So what we have here is, we have
again three intermediate steps.

00:45:55.360 --> 00:45:58.990
In the first step, of course,
we have an excited atom

00:45:58.990 --> 00:46:03.800
and a photon.

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:05.810
And we have the same here.

00:46:05.810 --> 00:46:09.450
But now the difference is,
that in the intermediate step,

00:46:09.450 --> 00:46:13.890
our energy defect is not
two atomic excitations,

00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:15.755
it is two photonic excitations.

00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:25.620
And now we want to
compare those two diagrams

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:31.565
for short and for long range.

00:46:38.790 --> 00:46:42.360
And it becomes clear
that short range

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:48.170
is where the frequency
of the photon--

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:49.680
its wavelength is lambda.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:52.410
Short range means
high frequency.

00:46:52.410 --> 00:46:54.450
The frequency of
the photon is larger

00:46:54.450 --> 00:46:56.980
than the atomic
excitation energy.

00:46:56.980 --> 00:46:59.480
Or that means, the
distance is smaller

00:46:59.480 --> 00:47:04.570
than the resonant
wavelength of the photon.

00:47:04.570 --> 00:47:09.750
Whereas, long range is
that the atomic excitation

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:11.835
is more precious than
the photonic excitation.

00:47:18.180 --> 00:47:18.780
OK.

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:25.330
So I need three more minutes.

00:47:25.330 --> 00:47:30.390
So it just fits
into the class time.

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:33.980
So we are here in
the limit that omega

00:47:33.980 --> 00:47:36.360
is larger than omega naught.

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:40.580
So that means, if we take now
the product of the three energy

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:44.400
denominators, omega
dominates over omega naught.

00:47:44.400 --> 00:47:47.400
So we'll have this structure
omega, omega naught, omega.

00:47:53.270 --> 00:47:55.435
Omega, omega naught, omega.

00:47:58.110 --> 00:48:01.950
Whereas, at long range,
omega naught dominates.

00:48:01.950 --> 00:48:05.030
We have omega naught,
omega naught, omega naught.

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:10.950
So the structure of the
product of energy denominators

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:13.616
is 1 over omega naught.

00:48:13.616 --> 00:48:17.890
If you look on the
right hand side,

00:48:17.890 --> 00:48:22.550
we have replaced-- in
the intermediate part

00:48:22.550 --> 00:48:26.100
in the propagator-- the
energy defect by omega naught

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:28.100
by omega.

00:48:28.100 --> 00:48:34.370
So therefore, in this case,
we have 1 over omega cubed

00:48:34.370 --> 00:48:39.000
and 1 over omega
naught squared, omega.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:42.110
So we know that when we
sum up over diagrams,

00:48:42.110 --> 00:48:45.680
we have to sum up over
all possibly diagrams.

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:51.040
And the ones which dominate
at short range are those ones

00:48:51.040 --> 00:48:53.110
and at long range
are the other ones.

00:48:58.290 --> 00:49:01.600
So in other words,
at short range,

00:49:01.600 --> 00:49:05.620
one photon is exchanged
and disappears.

00:49:05.620 --> 00:49:07.590
And then, the next photon comes.

00:49:07.590 --> 00:49:11.860
But at long range,
we have an exchange

00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:16.480
that one atom sends out two
photons almost simultaneously.

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:19.040
And the other atom absorbs them.

00:49:19.040 --> 00:49:21.570
Because it sends them out
almost simultaneously.

00:49:21.570 --> 00:49:25.470
Because here, we are talking
about long wavelength photons,

00:49:25.470 --> 00:49:28.260
and photons are cheaper.

00:49:28.260 --> 00:49:31.260
Rather send out two photons
before you spend too much time

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:33.920
in the excited state.

00:49:33.920 --> 00:49:34.420
OK.

00:49:34.420 --> 00:49:35.320
Let's wrap it up.

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:44.160
Since omega is proportional
to 1 over the wavelengths,

00:49:44.160 --> 00:49:47.540
which was-- and I said the
photons we are concentrating,

00:49:47.540 --> 00:49:59.566
is the photons which have a
wavelength of the distance, D .

00:49:59.566 --> 00:50:03.630
So what we are realizing
now is that, if you just

00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:11.840
compare those diagrams
at long range,

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:17.750
we go from 1 over omega
squared to 1 over omega.

00:50:17.750 --> 00:50:34.540
So at long range-- omega is--
we have an additional factor

00:50:34.540 --> 00:50:41.340
of omega, which is 1 over D.

00:50:41.340 --> 00:50:45.180
And so now, if you
assume-- I can't show you

00:50:45.180 --> 00:50:47.220
that without solving
the real problem--

00:50:47.220 --> 00:50:50.070
but if you assume
that at short range,

00:50:50.070 --> 00:50:55.860
we have 1 over R to the sixth--
van der Waals potential--

00:50:55.860 --> 00:50:59.590
then at least, I've proven
to you that at long range,

00:50:59.590 --> 00:51:01.690
you get one more
power in the distance.

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:09.500
And this is a transition from an
instantaneous potential, where

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:11.080
propagation effects
do not matter,

00:51:11.080 --> 00:51:13.905
to what is called
retarded potential.

00:51:24.340 --> 00:51:25.790
So that's all I
wanted to show you

00:51:25.790 --> 00:51:29.610
about interactions
between two neutral atoms.

